Eagers Automotive Ltd (APE.AX) Price Target

Valuation likely the key debate now with stock significantly above history. However, APE has a very different structural growth outlook and greater optionality even vs. two years ago. Compares will not be dealers/industry, but high- quality, structural growth, consumer discretionary names. Keep OW.

Another result that reinforced APE's long- term earnings power... First take here. 1) Efficiency alone an incremental +2ppt on margin or +67% lift vs. 3% PBT 1H25. 2) EA123 (fixed price used) a meaningful medium- term opportunity (we noted c.A \(\) 70m\$). 1H25 continued to reinforce conviction on unit economics and scalability. 3) Organic revenue growth - while we do not fully extrapolate 1H25 sales growth, we see continued scope to win share in new (and used), also a clear tailwind for higher- margin back end. ...And execution capability to close this gap: 1H25 A\(\) 198m\$ PBT, A \(\) 9- 15m\$ higher vs. 2H- 1H24 despite trough cycle (for most of) 1H and tougher compares (e.g., annual incentives/backlog release). Difference (and more) driven in large part by "operational improvement".

But stock has also re- rated materially, so where to from here...? Continued execution is still the core part of our thesis, but we see further upside: 1) Cycle improvements amplified with APE's share gains. Most of the last 12 months has been a trough cycle, with improvement only since May- June. 2) M&A and the ability to lift acquired margins (say \(

Bull base lifts to A\\$36/sh (A\\$25.20 previously) - As APE executes stronger than in our base case, including greater capital allocation (and discipline) lengthening the efficiency / operational improvement runway. We also see further increments from offshore expansion and strategic partnership. In our bull case, APE does not trade like a dealer, but more comparable to a high- quality, structural growth (with offshore expansion) consumer discretionary peers (e.g. ARB, BRG, LOV).

Bear case to A\\$16/sh (A\\$10 previously) - We assume further macro headwinds in our bear case, and more volatile earnings, including a shorter execution runway than we initially thought. Also, APE's initiatives around capital deployment, offshore and recent strategic partnership take longer to come to fruition and is less meaningful to earnings (at least over medium term).
Trading to optionality and execution

APE has operational optionality to preserve profitability and ultimately increase earnings - this was demonstrated at CY24 results, especially a 2H24 that showed margin stability (and even lift) despite a tougher operating environment, and now also 1H25.

We continue to back APE to execute on its structural initiatives. It continues to achieve what it can control. We see a long growth runway just from core strategy execution. We think APE is in the midst of a perception change, from "just a dealer" to greater appreciation of their structural growth runway, quality, and superior optionality (M&A, offshore, strategic partnerships)
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research
Electric Vehicles: Positive Self- help: Positive

More than eager: APE executes strongly on key drivers in its control (EA123, network optimisation, F&l penetration, incremental market share), together with higher margins for longer. Our bull case also takes into account EV tailwinds and APE's disciplined capital allocation (e.g., 5.7% stake in MMS and bringing Retail JV to 80% ownership), providing further earnings and share price upside. The Retail JV thesis also plays out, generating strong growth and returns.

Eager to deliver: Structurally, we see profitability upside from: 1) fixed- price used vehicles; 2) network optimisation; 3) finance penetration; 4) structurally higher "margin on the metal"; and 5) clear EV alignment and tailwinds. Cyclically, we see scope for macro tailwinds (which are likely to at least help sentiment) and bake in small PBT margin lifts (being more conservative vs APE's outlook of potential improvement).

Macro over micro: The organic growth environment remains tough, with vehicle sales taking a leg down, then remaining lower for longer amid broader macro headwinds, higher interest rates and inflation. In the medium term, finance penetration remains at 35%, APE reinvests harder in fixed price used but sales volumes do not meaningfully increase, and only minor further cost- out is achieved. We also see lower for longer demand for new cars in our bear case - including in the Retail JV.
